data.title: Play Date at Pete's
data.description: Every third Monday at Play Date at Pete's, hear readings of brand new plays from some of New York's most exciting emerging playwrights and actors. Hosted by Alle Mims and Andy Boyd, this series has existed since 2015, when it was founded by Willie Johnson. Come hear some new plays and meet the future stars of tomorrow while they're still working day jobs!

data.title: Silent Writing Happy Hour
data.description: Taking inspiration from the infinite canon of literature past and present, we present weekly short readings, inspiring 30-minute exercises, offering writers the space and direction to write silently and hone their skills. Writers may share their writing, as the spirit and time dictates. The last portion of the evening is devoted to self-directed work on whatever project you have that merits such.

data.title: Astronomy on Tap
data.description: Join us for Astro on Tap NYC #157 ‚Äì Pride! Looking at queer space(s) and a new research telescope. Hosted by MC Tycho Brewhaha aka Brian Levine, our events are fun and informative so you can learn stuff and have fun while you drink. Each event features engaging talks by professional scientists, educators, and other astronomy-related enthusiasts, plenty of Q&A time, and trivia with prizes. It‚Äôs out of this world!

data.title: Trivia
data.description: NYC's finest trivia beckons. Got the brains? Bring your friends and wrack your noodles with six rounds of clever, fun, HARD trivia. The most experienced trivia hosts in the city will test your mental mettle in areas of General Knowledge, Music, Top Tens, and Visual Identification. First Prize is a $75 bar tab, Second Prize is a $40 bar tab and Third Prize is a $15 bar tab. But the real prize (besides bragging rights for those who place, and a berth in the twice yearly finals) is the time honored social scene of the Quizz-Off crowd. Give it a try smart guy! And come early for a good table.

data.title: Kweendom
data.description: Don't miss the show TimeOUT called "consistently dope" and Thrillist described as "extremely gay." Featuring an always fresh lineup of only LGBTQ performers, Kweendom is one of NYC's most beloved comedy showcases. Catch stand-up, storytelling, characters, music and more from up-and-coming artists, as well as faces from TV and streaming. Always free, with donations accepted for a designated LGBTQ-foused organization each show. Come for the laughs, stay for the fresh faces in your Grindr grid. (Bring Kweendom home with you in the new collection of essays, Welcome to Kweendom, available now!)

data.title: Climate Cafe: Songs of Connection
data.description: Join us for a community conversation about climate grief. Together we will explore our fears, anxieties, hopes, and yearnings for a world in ecological crisis. Through a series of guided discussion questions, reflections, music, and good old fashioned hanging out at a great bar, we will experience what it means to have our grief witnessed, held, and transformed into healing medicine. Each Climate Cafe will feature a musical performance by a guest artist. Come share, listen, heal, and make new friends. All are welcome. Register at the link.

data.title: Chestnut: A Live Storytelling Hour
data.description:
In the spirit of liberation and celebration what‚Äôs a time when you were on top? Prepare a story about your craziest party, a victory you didn‚Äôt see coming, or that mountain you finally climbed after 5 years of planning. Think back to that bottle of tequila or a sunny day after a storm. Whether it was a win for the soul or fireworks literally lit up the sky, sometimes we need a reminder to celebrate the big and the small. 

In case you need anymore inspiration I invite you to think back to those milestones: prom, 21st birthday, that wedding your cousin had in the woods, or the 30th birthday party that was more of a rave.

Bring a story, a friend, or simply yourselves.

data.title: Poet William May Book Event with Special Guest Host Q&A
data.description: Join us for a special evening with poet William May as he celebrates the release of his debut poetry collection, Blaze Without Burning, published by Finishing Line Press. A fourth-generation native of New York‚Äôs Greenwich Village, May brings a lifetime of lived experience and literary insight to his work. The event will feature a moderated Q&A with a special guest host and live reading, offering an intimate look into the themes of strength, transformation, and human connection that shape the collection. Notably, the chapbook‚Äôs innovative twin-poem structure invites readers to explore dual perspectives on shared themes, creating a layered emotional experience. This public gathering promises to be a meaningful exchange between author and audience in a venue that beautifully complements May‚Äôs deep-rooted connection to the city's creative legacy.

data.title: Vaclav Havel's PROTEST
data.description: A reading of the short play, PROTEST, by Vaclav Havel, to benefit immigrants being harassed or deported by the US government. What does it mean to "live in truth" in a society in which a majority of citizens appears happy to ignore untruths or doesn't know how to resist them? This darkly funny play exposes the very real pressures put on citizens of good will who nonetheless bend in the face of wrong. Performed by Drew Valins and David Millstone
